post_text: COVID-19 Update-The Commerce City School System has completed Day 25 of the 20-21 school year! As of this afternoon, our system has two active COVID-19 cases across the district, including both students and staff. Our school nurses are working closely with the Department of Health to conduct contact tracing. As of today, we have forty-one students or staff members who have had to quarantine as a result of contact with a student or staff member. In the event of a positive case, individuals identified as being within six feet or less for 15 minutes or more beginning two days before the positive person had symptoms or their test sample was taken would be required to quarantine for 14 days. Schools will continue to work with students and teachers if they transition to working remotely during a quarantine period.

As of today, we have six students or staff members who have had to quarantine as a result of contact with a student or staff member. In the event of a positive case, individuals identified as being within six feet or less for 15 minutes or more beginning two days before the positive person had symptoms or their test sample was taken would be required to quarantine for 14 days. Schools will continue to work with students and teachers if they transition to working remotely during a quarantine period.

Commerce High School FFA
September 1 at 9:34 AM ·

Mr. Robin Richards has been selected as the Commerce FFA Faculty/Staff Member of the Month!

When we needed to switch locations for our August meeting in a hurry, Mr. Richards stepped up and helped us to change around the gym in order to accommodate our members and our “Welcome Back Wiffle Ball” game. In addition to this, you can find Mr. Richards mentoring and coaching six of our very best FFA members each day in the volleyball court.

This recognition came with a sign to display outside of his classroom as well as a small gift. Please join us in congratulating Mr. Robin Richards!

#AlwaysReady

In order to comply with social distancing guidelines, we are limiting entry to home football games to 50% max stadium capacity. All Super Tiger pass holders will be guaranteed entry into all home football games, including the first right to purchase playoff tickets. Remaining tickets will be presold online via GOFAN and any leftover tickets will be sold at the gate until sold out. Be sure to get your Super Tiger tickets so you will not have to miss a game. Super Tiger tickets will be sold Thursday, August 3rd at Ray Lamb Stadium beginning at 6:30 PM or you can contact Ray Beck directly at 253-222-3369.

Go Tigers,

Will Smith

COVID- Update

The Commerce City School System has completed Day 16 of the 20-21 school year! As of this afternoon, our system has zero active COVID-19 cases across the district, including both students and staff. Our school nurses are working closely with the Department of Health to conduct contact tracing. As of today, we have not had any students or staff members who have had to quarantine as a result of contact with a student or staff member. In the event of a positive case, individuals identified as being within six feet or less for 15 minutes or more beginning two days before the positive person had symptoms or their test sample was taken would be required to quarantine for 14 days. Schools will continue to work with students and teachers if they transition to working remotely during a quarantine period.

shared_text:
Commerce High School
August 24 at 8:12 AM ·

On Tuesday August 25th, history will be made as we host the first ever home volleyball tri-match in Commerce history.

We will play Cedar Shoals at 5pm and Oglethorpe Co. at 7pm. Tickets are $7 for all three matches (if you have the Tiger Sports pass our five events alone make up almost 70% of the cost of the card itself).

Doors open around 4:15pm and the team run on will be at 4:30 with warm-up starting right after.

We hope you're able to make it for this historic evening. Please remember to socially distance in the Gym and wear masks, especially if seated near the benches. Let's go 🐯🏐!

Also the Fit to a Tee store is open until Friday 8/28 at 5pm. Once it closes no more inaugural season shirts will be made. Fit to a Tee needs at least nine more shirt orders to print the minimum twelve needed so use this link to order anything in time for when the Area matches begin on September 8th.

https://fit-to-a-tee-promotions-inc.printavo.com/merch/commercevolleyball

Commerce City Schools
August 6 at 8:13 AM ·

Breakfasts/Lunches for Remote Learners:
Families of students doing remote learning and wishing to receive meals will receive detailed information on the process on Monday August 10th.
Ordering for those meals will be online by Friday of each week (beginning next week by August 14th) for pickup on Tuesday afternoon (beginning August 18th).
Pickup will be every Tuesday afternoon (beginning August 18th) at the High School loading dock from 1:30om-2:30pm. Each student will receive a bag with 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches . This is not FREE Emergency feeding such as meal service this past March-May. This is part of the National School Lunch Program and meals will be charged by eligibility. We urge families to complete a new Free/Reduced Application through the Parent Portal by clicking “More” and then “Meal Eligibility”

post_text:
** Distance Learning Update **

For those that have opted in for distance learning AND have requested a school-issued device. Devices can be picked up tomorrow, August 5th and Thursday, August 6th between 8AM - 3PM at the school your child attends.

A $25 protection plan must be purchased for each device. The fee must be paid on SchoolPay prior to picking up a device or in cash (exact change if possible) at the time of pickup. No checks will be accepted.

If your student(s) checked out a device in the spring and it was not returned or there were fees for damages, those fees must be paid before another device will be issued. Fees to be paid on SchoolPay (link on our website) or cash at the school.

Instructions on accessing Edgenuity are still being prepared and will be made available as soon as possible.

School Traffic Change

Lakeview Drive, starting at Waterworks Road and continuing through its intersection with Minish Drive
will be a two-way street 24 hours a day, 7 days a week; having no section of the road as a one-way street.
During the school hours Lakeview Drive WILL NOT be a One Way Street

Start now preparing your drive to school, traffic will be congested as the students return to class.

Add extra time to your drive to school the first few weeks as the bus traffic,
student traffic and parent traffic uses the new route.

Be careful and Drive patient with the new change.

Have a great school year Tigers!!!!

Dear CHS Family,
It is with tremendous sadness that I share with you the loss of a member of the Tiger family. Evan Davis, a senior at Commerce High School was killed in a vehicle accident on July 15th.
Nothing can prepare us for the loss of a friend or loved one. The most important thing that we can do during this difficult time is support one another, and remember to cherish our friends and family every day of our lives.
“Once a Tiger, Always a Tiger”

Love you and Go Tigers

Will Smith

post_text:
The Georgia Broadband Deployment Initiative (GBDI) is launching the Speedtest by Ookla® pilot project statewide through August. This (very) quick and easy test will provide actual upload and download times at the location of access, so it will give much needed information about what parts of the state are able to successfully access the Internet.

Georgians are encouraged to download the free Ookla Speedtest app (Android or iOS-Apple) to the various devices that they use to connect to the internet (smartphones, tablets, laptops, and desktop computers) and take several tests in the places where connectivity is important to them. The easy-to-use Speedtest, along with the information available at the Broadband Initiative website, will assist school leaders as they plan for their digital learning strategies.

Click here for more information: https://gov.georgia.gov/press-releases/2020-06-23/state-launches-internet-speedtest-pilot-schools

PARENTS: The coronavirus has presented new challenges for all of us -- students, parents, and staff. Now that we have concluded the 2019-2020 school year, we would your feedback so we can improve the process and further plan for the 2020-2021 school year. Please take a few minutes to complete a short survey about your experience with distance learning and your observations of your children's experiences. The survey link will be posted in the Infinite Campus Parent Portal. We will also be sending the link by email today, so be on the lookout! We would greatly appreciate your feedback.

If you need assistance accessing the Parent Portal, email us at parentportal@commercecityschools.org or give us a call at 706-335-5500.

This afternoon Dr. Tolbert and I spoke directly with Governor Kemp’s office. In order to abide by the current restrictions and guidelines we are unable to hold a CHS Prom this year. While I want all of my students to have a memorable high school experience, we must adhere to state guidelines. Prom or no Prom, you will always be our great CHS Tigers. At this moment we are working hard to keep our 2020 CHS Graduation on May 22nd. We will keep everyone updated as new information is released. Students will be allowed to pick up refunds on May 19-21st.
Go Tigers!

Will Smith

This upcoming week is “Teacher Appreciation Week”!

Challenge for students:

Write on a blank sheet of paper a teacher you are thankful for with a little message and then take a picture of them holding their sign. We will post it on our social media throughout the week to encourage our educators! What a great way to show our appreciation!

Example: “I’m thankful for Mrs. Smith and her Social Studies class. She is awesome and I miss her!”

Send it to this account or brit.jones@commercecityschools.org

Thank You!

post_text:
Class of 2020. We are excited to announce that every senior Commerce Tiger will have a banner displayed on the light poles down town. With help from personal donors, CHS, and the City of Commerce, they will begin putting them up Tuesday and continue until they are all displayed. They will be in alphabetical order.

I would love to see each senior take a picture with their banner and send to my email. Class of 2020, stay positive and stay strong. Do me a favor and spend some time reaching out to your classmates and encourage them to do the same. Miss you and Go Tigers!!!

Thank you,

Will Smith.

post_text:
New Wi-Fi Hotspots for Students

We have just received and deployed several mobile Wi-Fi hotspots in the community for our students in need. Students that would like to use the Wi-Fi hotspots are asked to reach out to their teachers for the connection password. We would like to thank the Jackson EMC Foundation for making this purchase possible. We would also like to thank the following businesses and organizations for allowing us to place the hotspots at their locations. The connection is available in the parking areas of the following locations.

1) Graceful Gospel Dance Academy (Quality Foods Shopping Center)

2) Boys & Girls Club of Jackson County

3) Commerce Housing Authority

4) Commerce Recreation Department

Any questions can be directed to Tobie Jones, Technology Director. tobie.jones@commercecityschools.org

post_text: Due to incoming weather tomorrow, the first stops for food delivery will begin at 10:00 am at Quality Foods, Crestview Village. Bellview Homes will be from 10-10:15. Today we are highlighting the fantastic Mr. Demarco Hernandez from Commerce High School! In the fall, Demarco will run at Emmanuel College on an athletic scholarship he worked very hard over the past two years to earn! Not only is he extremely dedicated to his sport, he is also an outstanding student and an amazing brother and role model to all his siblings; especially his special needs sister. Demarco has worked hard his entire academic career to constantly achieve and surpass his goals. Demarco is compassionate, driven, and focused in every aspect of his life.

We are so proud of you and hope you feel extra special today! Keep spreading the drive to everyone around you and we can't wait to see all you continue to do!

#SNRSZN #SeniorSpotlights #SISeniors #CO2020

post_text:
If our students return on Monday, April 27, we will follow the schedule below for PreK and Kindergarten registration.

PreK Registration-
Parents of PreK students for 2020-2021 need to complete the online registration packet. When complete, please email Angie Ingram (angie.ingram@commercecityschools.org) to set up an appointment to bring required documentation to Central Office.

Kindergarten Registration-
May 5th- Parents may call the school (706-335-5587) to make appointments.
May 16th (Saturday)- Kindergarten Round-up

If school closures extend beyond Friday, April 24, these deadlines will be extended. Thanks for your patience.
